# Rate Limiting Strategy — Complete Reference

This document is the authoritative reference for all rate limiting in the Hestia application.

## Architecture: Two-Layer Defense

```
Request from browser/app
  |
  v
Layer 1: CloudFront WAF (edge)
  |-- Blocks at CDN edge, request never reaches backend
  |-- Per-IP rate limiting (no resource-level granularity)
  |-- AWS-managed, survives deploys/restarts
  |-- Returns 429 with JSON error body
  |
  v
Layer 2: Application Rate Limiter (Spring Boot)
  |-- Blocks at app level, request reaches backend but doesn't write to DB
  |-- Per-IP + per-resource granularity (e.g., per invitation ID)
  |-- In-memory (ConcurrentHashMap), resets on deploy
  |-- Returns success silently (fire-and-forget endpoints) or throws exception
  |
  v
Layer 3: Database Idempotency (PostgreSQL)
  |-- Final safety net for data integrity
  |-- WHERE clauses, unique constraints, atomic increments
  |-- Always active, no configuration needed
```

### Why Both Layers?

- **WAF alone isn't enough**: Can't rate-limit per resource ID. An attacker with 1 IP sending 10 requests for 1,000 different invitations = 10,000 requests, all passing WAF.
- **App alone isn't enough**: Every request hits EC2 compute + opens a DB connection. On t4g.micro (1GB RAM), high volume burns CPU and connection pool even if the rate limiter drops requests.
- **Together**: WAF caps total volume at the edge. App caps per-resource abuse. DB prevents data corruption as the final net.

